    "literature": "\n      <h3>4. Deep Literature Review And Positioning</h3>\n      <p>This literature starts from Bayesian mechanism design, Mirrlees-Holmstrom contract theory, Myerson auction design, and monopoly pricing. Robust design changes the informational premise: the designer may not know the prior, correlation, information structure, technology, or segmentation.</p>\n      <p>Closest neighboring lines include Bergemann-Morris robust mechanism design, Carroll-style robust contracts, Brooks-Du informationally robust auctions, prior-free mechanism design, and Bergemann-Brooks-Morris robust price-discrimination/segmentation.</p>\n      <p><strong>Paper-specific position.</strong> Studies exchange mechanisms that remain incentive compatible and individually rational under weak informational assumptions.</p>\n    ",
    "proof": "\n      <h3>5. Detailed Proof Techniques And Mathematical Tools</h3>\n      <h3>Tool 1: Minimax / Duality</h3>\n      <div class=\"theorem-box\">\n        <p>A typical proof shows</p>\n        <div class=\"math\">\n          \\[\n            \\sup_m\\inf_u W(m,u)\n            \\le\n            \\inf_{\\lambda\\in\\Lambda}D(\\lambda),\n          \\]\n        </div>\n        <p>then constructs (m^*) and a worst-case (u^*) or dual certificate (lambda^*) where equality holds.</p>\n      </div>\n      <h3>Tool 2: Incentive-Constraint Geometry</h3>\n      <p>Robustness often converts Bayesian incentive constraints into ex post, dominant-strategy, maxmin, or obedience constraints. The proof becomes a geometry problem over feasible payoff or allocation rules.</p>\n      <h3>Tool 3: Extremal Environments</h3>\n      <p>Worst-case distributions are often simple: two-point distributions, Pareto tails, perfectly pooled signals, fully segmented markets, or information structures that make rents hardest to extract.</p>\n    ",
