  "carroll-walton-2022-framework-contracting": {
    "setup": "\n      <p><strong>Source.</strong> <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.09129\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer\">https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.09129</a></p>\n      <p><strong>Paper.</strong> A General Framework for Robust Contracting Models. <strong>Authors.</strong> Daniel Walton; Gabriel Carroll. <strong>Venue.</strong> Econometrica, 2022. <strong>Research family.</strong> robust contract theory.</p>\n      <h3>0. Detailed Model Setup</h3>\n      <p>The robust-design primitive is an uncertainty set (mathcal U). In Bayesian design, the designer fixes one (uinmathcal U). In robust design, the rule must perform well for all (uinmathcal U), or at least against the worst one.</p>\n      <div class=\"math\">\n        \\[\n          V^{rob}\n          =\n          \\sup_{m\\in\\mathcal M}\n          \\inf_{u\\in\\mathcal U}\n          W(m,u).\n        \\]\n      </div>\n      <p>The paper-specific uncertainty is: Unifies robust contracting models by clarifying which uncertainty sets and incentive constraints generate simple optimal contracts.</p>\n      <p>The designer's object may be a contract, direct mechanism, auction, pricing rule, segmentation, or recommendation policy. Incentive constraints are imposed either ex post, in dominant strategies, for every information structure, or through Bayes-correlated obedience constraints.</p>\n    ",
    "results": "\n      <h3>1 &amp; 2. Main Results And Theorems</h3>\n      <div class=\"theorem-box\">\n        <h3>Formal Robust-Design Statement</h3>\n        <p>For the relevant class of rules (mathcal M) and uncertainty set (mathcal U), the paper identifies a rule (m^*) and a value (V^*) such that</p>\n        <div class=\"math\">\n          \\[\n            \\inf_{u\\in\\mathcal U}W(m^*,u)=V^*\n            =\n            \\sup_{m\\in\\mathcal M}\\inf_{u\\in\\mathcal U}W(m,u).\n          \\]\n        </div>\n        <p><strong>Paper-specific theorem in words.</strong> The paper gives a general framework for deriving robust contracts and relating many earlier robust-contracting results.</p>\n      </div>\n      <p><strong>Intuition.</strong> A robust rule is not optimized for the average environment. It is chosen so that an adversarial prior, signal structure, technology, or market segmentation cannot make performance fall below the guaranteed bound.</p>\n    ",
    "example": "\n      <h3>3. Concrete / Simple Example</h3>\n      \n      <h3>Robust Linear Contract Example</h3>\n      <p>An agent chooses effort \\(a\\in[0,1]\\). Output is \\(y=a+\\varepsilon\\), but the principal is unsure about the distribution of \\(\\varepsilon\\). A linear contract pays \\(w(y)=\\alpha y+\\beta\\). If the agent's effort cost is \\(c(a)=a^2/2\\), the agent solves</p>\n      <div class=\"math\">\n        \\[\n          \\max_a \\alpha a-\\frac{a^2}{2}.\n        \\]\n      </div>\n      <p>The first-order condition is \\(a=\\alpha\\). Thus the share \\(\\alpha\\) implements effort without needing the full distribution of noise. The principal's robust problem chooses \\(\\alpha\\) to trade off incentive provision and rent/noise exposure.</p>\n    \n      <h3>Mapping To This Paper</h3>\n      <p>In this paper, replace the toy uncertainty set by the paper's object: Unifies robust contracting models by clarifying which uncertainty sets and incentive constraints generate simple optimal contracts. The core calculation remains the same: write the worst-case payoff, derive the candidate rule, and then prove no other rule can guarantee more.</p>\n    ",
    "literature": "\n      <h3>4. Deep Literature Review And Positioning</h3>\n      <p>This literature starts from Bayesian mechanism design, Mirrlees-Holmstrom contract theory, Myerson auction design, and monopoly pricing. Robust design changes the informational premise: the designer may not know the prior, correlation, information structure, technology, or segmentation.</p>\n      <p>Closest neighboring lines include Bergemann-Morris robust mechanism design, Carroll-style robust contracts, Brooks-Du informationally robust auctions, prior-free mechanism design, and Bergemann-Brooks-Morris robust price-discrimination/segmentation.</p>\n      <p><strong>Paper-specific position.</strong> Unifies robust contracting models by clarifying which uncertainty sets and incentive constraints generate simple optimal contracts.</p>\n    ",
    "proof": "\n      <h3>5. Detailed Proof Techniques And Mathematical Tools</h3>\n      <h3>Tool 1: Minimax / Duality</h3>\n      <div class=\"theorem-box\">\n        <p>A typical proof shows</p>\n        <div class=\"math\">\n          \\[\n            \\sup_m\\inf_u W(m,u)\n            \\le\n            \\inf_{\\lambda\\in\\Lambda}D(\\lambda),\n          \\]\n        </div>\n        <p>then constructs (m^*) and a worst-case (u^*) or dual certificate (lambda^*) where equality holds.</p>\n      </div>\n      <h3>Tool 2: Incentive-Constraint Geometry</h3>\n      <p>Robustness often converts Bayesian incentive constraints into ex post, dominant-strategy, maxmin, or obedience constraints. The proof becomes a geometry problem over feasible payoff or allocation rules.</p>\n      <h3>Tool 3: Extremal Environments</h3>\n      <p>Worst-case distributions are often simple: two-point distributions, Pareto tails, perfectly pooled signals, fully segmented markets, or information structures that make rents hardest to extract.</p>\n    ",
    "critique": "\n      <h3>6. Critical Discussion, Open Questions, And Limitations</h3>\n      <p><strong>Problem solved.</strong> The paper gives a general framework for deriving robust contracts and relating many earlier robust-contracting results.</p>\n      <p><strong>Limitation.</strong> Robustness depends on the chosen uncertainty set (mathcal U). If (mathcal U) is too small, the result is fragile; if too large, the robust rule may be too conservative.</p>\n      <p><strong>Open question.</strong> Can the uncertainty set be learned from data? Can robust mechanisms adapt over time without becoming manipulable? How should robustness interact with fairness, privacy, and platform data?</p>\n      <p><strong>Research idea.</strong> A natural extension is dynamic robust design: the mechanism starts prior-free, observes outcomes, updates the uncertainty set, and must remain incentive compatible while learning.</p>\n    "
  },
